track_notes:
There is no trail from the north side of this peak. Since Google Earth images were taken in 2002 there has been logging on the north side below the final ridge.
At first the path parallels a small stream, then breaks out into a logged area that is followed easily up to a small col where the final ridge is followed through trees to the top.
Once on top travel is easy, this is part of the Hunchback Hills horseshoe, described in Gillean Dafferns guide to Kananaskis, but that is a much longer approach to this peak.

With no recognized trail on the north slopes of Stony Peak, several routes have been tried. This route follows a logging cut for about half the distance, before climbing onto the ridge which is followed to the summit. It is a reasonable route whose main draw-back is the last few hundred feet of ascent up the eastern side of a bare hill-side. If there is a wind, it will sure blow hard across this section!
Bell cell-phone service is available on the summit

From the trailhead follow the slight track in and up a ridge walk to the saddle between Stony and Lusk N2
On a safety scale out of five (5 being hard, exposed and 1 walking up a sidewalk) I would rate this as a 3. There is limited route finding and little exposure
